{"questionId":"3487927","questionHtml":"<p>Find the single matrix that represents the transformation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>T</mi></math>, which will undo the transformation described above.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1 (find product of matrices first)</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>'</mo></math>&nbsp;is represented by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">Q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>7</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>recognizing need to find their <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">Q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">P</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong> (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">Q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">P</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>7</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>78</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>7</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR</strong>&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0897435</mn><mo>…</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0256410</mn><mo>…</mo></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0384615</mn><mo>…</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>153846</mn><mo>…</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong> A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2 (find inverses of both matrices first)</strong></p>\n<p>recognizing need to find inverse of both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">P</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">Q</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">P</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; <strong>AND</strong>&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">Q</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>13</mn></mfrac></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>13</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>13</mn></mfrac></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>13</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>T</mi></math> is represented by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">P</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">Q</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>78</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>7</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR</strong>&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0897435</mn><mo>…</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0256410</mn><mo>…</mo></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0384615</mn><mo>…</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>153846</mn><mo>…</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong> A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> In METHOD 1, award <em><strong>M1A0M1A0</strong></em> if they multiply the matrices in the wrong order.</p>\n<p>In METHOD 2, award <em><strong>M1A1M1A0</strong></em> if they multiply the matrices in the wrong order.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"3487927","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ2.13a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the single matrix that represents the transformation T'→T, which will undo the transformation described above.","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.9—Matrix transformations","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.14—Introduction to matrices"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}